             </div>
          </div>

          <div className="mt-12 flex items-center gap-3 justify-center text-brand-gold opacity-60">
             <CheckCircle size={14} />
             <span className="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest font-bold">Money Back Guarantee</span>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  );
};

payload.text:
To answer your question: **We should set up the Database first.**

Here is the logic:
1.  **Inventory Source:** You need a place to store your products so the website knows what to sell.
2.  **Order Record:** When a payment happens later, you need a database ready to instantly catch and save that order details. If you do payment first, you might lose order info!

Regarding **"what needs to be pasted in Firebase"**, there are usually two things people look for:

1.  **The Config (Code):** You need to copy the *Project Settings* from the Firebase Console and paste them into your `firebase.ts` file (replacing the placeholders I put there).
2.  **The Security Rules (Firebase Console):** Since we are in development, you need to paste these "Open" rules into the **Firestore Database -> Rules** tab and **Storage -> Rules** tab in the Firebase Console so your app can actually read/write data.

**Paste this into Firebase Console -> Firestore Database -> Rules:**
```text
rules_version = '2';
service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {
    match /{document=**} {
      allow read, write: if true;
    }
  }
}
```

**Paste this into Firebase Console -> Storage -> Rules:**
```text
rules_version = '2';
service firebase.storage {
  match /b/{bucket}/o {
    match /{allPaths=**} {
      allow read, write: if true;
    }
  }
}
```

---

### App Update: "Seed" Button
To make sure your "product info, photo and detail" are saved to Firebase immediately, I have updated the **Admin Dashboard**. I added a **"Load Sample Data"** button.

When you log in to the admin panel, if your database is empty, you can click this button to instantly upload the hardcoded products from your code into your new Firebase Database.

